{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f6c18f50-7315-468b-8106-e056b295fd1f","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions). They contain the stack trace, exception type, and thread state.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need a full memory dump for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n/usr/libexec/PlistBuddy -c \"Add :com.apple.CrashReporter.UseSpindump bool false\" ~/Library/Preferences/com.apple.CrashReporter.plist\n```\n\nThen reproduce the crash — the core file will appear in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can load it with:\n\n```bash\nlldb ./YourApp -c /cores/core.12345\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c8d50537-c00c-4a08-a4ef-50671b172ee3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":339},"id":"d96d50fa-0bd9-445e-aa46-324a21757b83","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:59:31.754Z","parentId":"f5ac4f64-b6b9-4f53-be7a-e8b202c327f0"}
